<HEADLINE>
FT  23 NOV 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Midweek's television, like the midweek joint, coming round again as
rissoles, has a dull, marking-time feel to it. Regulars include Between the
Lines (9.30pm BBC1), which has lost its bite since its principal coppers
were booted out of the force. The old setting - police investigating
complaints against the police - had a frighteningly contagious tendency to
paranoia and conspiracy theories. The new format is still watchable but
disappointingly conventional.
A big night for sport, with Oo-ah Cantona, an entente cordiale on his own,
returning to Manchester United in The Champions League (7.20pm, ITV), while
boxing features prominently in BBC 1's Sportsnight (10.20pm). Those who do
not find Baldrick in Blackadder the most uningratiatingly unfunny stooge in
the history of comedy will like Tony Robinson's trip to the Caribbean in
this week's Great Journeys (9.25pm, BBC2). Or try Syrup, a Cannes
prizewinner in the Short and Curlies series (9.45pm, Channel 4), the
engaging mini-fable of poor little Baldy George, who finds fulfilment one
lunch-hour with the acquisition of a head of thatch.
</TEXT>
