<HEADLINE>
FT  23 NOV 94 / Executive share option schemes 'lack performance targets'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Some two-thirds of UK-listed companies are operating executive share option
schemes without any performance targets, KPMG Peat Marwick said.
A survey by the accountancy firm of 374 companies listed on the London Stock
Exchange with executive share option schemes found that some Pounds 7bn of
the Pounds 10.5bn of publicly quoted shares allocated to executive option
schemes do not refer to performance.
Mr David Tuch, a KPMG tax partner, said: 'It is clear from our survey that
in the vast majority of the original schemes, there was no attempt to link
the company's performance in any way to the rewards via share options . . .
a senior executive could expect.'
While this was now changing, he said, only slightly more than half the
companies introducing schemes since 1988 had performance targets.
Mr Tuch said the report highlighted a need for schemes to be more closely
related to performance:
'Executive share options should be powerful performance motivators for
directors, linking their rewards to those of shareholders.'
The government is under pressure to end the income tax exemption for Inland
Revenue-approved schemes. This was introduced in 1984 and led to a
proliferation of schemes giving executives the right to acquire shares in
the future, usually at a price based on the share price at the time the
option was granted.
The schemes were initially popular because they were financed by equity
rather than profits, but companies have been under pressure from
institutions to introduce option performance targets.
The survey found some 74 per cent of schemes with performance targets used
formulae linked to earnings per share, although this was losing its
popularity.
Executive Share Options and Performance Targets. KPMG Peat Marwick, 1 Puddle
Dock, Blackfriars, London EC4V 3PD. Free.
Cutting the head count, Page 15
</TEXT>
