<HEADLINE>
FT  23 NOV 94 / Gas pay rises 'outstrip others'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Staff in the gas industry have experienced pay increases above the average
for the whole economy, the Chartered Institute of Public Finance and
Accountancy says today, Motoko Rich writes.
Following attacks on British Gas for giving Mr Cedric Brown, its chief
executive, a 75 per cent pay rise, a study by the institute found that gas
industry earnings have risen 42.8 per cent since 1990 as opposed to 23.8 per
cent in the whole economy.
The study also found that among all the privatised utilities - gas,
telecommunications, electricity, and water - employees have received
increases above the average rate in all industries.
When looking at weekly earnings, the study also found that in the economy as
a whole 30 per cent of full-time adult workers earn less than Pounds 220 per
week. But in the regulated industries under 10 per cent of employees earn
less than that.
