<HEADLINE>
FT  23 NOV 94 / ScottishPower launches telecoms subsidiary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ScottishPower yesterday launched a telecommunications subsidiary to compete
with British Telecommunications and Mercury for the provision of business
services in Scotland.
ScottishTelecom will use an optical fibre network which is being installed
at a cost of Pounds 35m alongside ScottishPower's overhead and underground
cables in central Scotland.
The company claims customers making a mixture of local and long-distance
calls via an exchange will achieve savings on call charges compared with BT
and Mercury of between 20 per cent and 30 per cent.
ScottishTelecom will introduce a standard Scottish rate for calls, other
than local calls, to anywhere in Scotland. It believes BT and Mercury, which
charge a long-distance rate for calls between cities will find it hard to
respond to its Scottish rate.
ScottishTelecom is the latest development in ScottishPower's strategy of
diversifying from its core electricity business. It already has a gas
subsidiary, CaledonianGas, and has expanded in retailing by buying many of
the Clydesdale Group's electrical goods stores from the receiver.
Mr Rod Matthews, ScottishTelecom chief executive, said all the current
telecommunications operators had tariffs 'biased towards the large
metropolitan areas, with London enjoying a number of special advantages on
top of that'.
ScottishTelecom has a partnership agreement with Energis, the
telecommunications network owned by the National Grid company, which began
operating this year. ScottishTelecom will use Energis's network south of the
border. It will use Colt's network in the City of London.
ScottishTelecom has not established connections to Aberdeen, Dundee and
other places in Scottish Hydro-Electric's electricity franchise area, but is
discussing using Hydro-Electric's telecommunications system or installing
its own.
ScottishTelecom has already begun providing services to a small number of
large users such as the BBC and will offer its full range of services from
next March. Full scale marketing began yesterday.
</TEXT>
