<HEADLINE>
FT  23 NOV 94 / Lib Dems flesh out Bank reform plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Malcolm Bruce, the Liberal Democrats' Treasury spokesman, is to put
forward detailed plans for a reform of the Bank of England, giving it
greater independence from the government and the institutions of the City of
London.
Mr Bruce is to flesh out his party's commitment to giving the Bank greater
control over the setting of interest rates.
Presenting his party's alternative Budget tomorrow, Mr Bruce will call for
the Bank's role to be modelled along the lines of the New Zealand Central
Bank, with the government setting a broad inflation target and the Bank
having total control over the setting of monetary policy.
He will also call for the Bank to appoint executive directors from the
regions to play a crucial role in the setting of monetary policy. These
representatives will vote on monetary policy changes, enjoying powers
similar to those of the regional governors of the US Federal Reserve and
Germany's Bundesbank.
The Liberal Democrats will make clear that they are committed to widening
the inflation target within which the UK monetary authorities are operating.
The Bank implied in a recent Inflation Report that it was using a target
range for inflation of 1 per cent to 2.5 per cent up to the next general
election.
Mr Bruce believes this target will require the government to raise interest
rates too sharply. He is proposing a broader band of zero to 3 per cent for
the coming years.
The Liberal Democrats remain the only party committed to creating a
completely independent central bank for the UK.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, has given the Bank greater power in the
setting of interest rates by publishing the minutes of the monthly meeting
between himself and Mr Eddie George, the Bank of England's governor.
The Liberal Democrats say that the government can only pursue a credible
counter-inflationary policy by abandoning political constraints and giving
the Bank full control over monetary policy. They plan to publish a detailed
policy document on the issue early next year.
The party would want to ensure that local variations in inflation, wages and
growth were taken into account when setting policy by appointing regional
directors to the Bank.
The Liberal Democrats say that the style of the Bank is too heavily
influenced by movements in financial markets, especially bonds and
currencies.
They would create a 'policymaking executive', modelled on the Bundesbank
council, in which central and regional directors would vote on policy
changes.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
