<HEADLINE>
FT  23 NOV 94 / Ministers study BAe's RAF offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD GRAY, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An offer by British Aerospace to maintain the Royal Air Force's existing
fleet of Hercules transport aircraft at a fixed price, with a set number of
aircraft available at any one time, is to be discussed by a cabinet
committee tomorrow.
The proposal, which was sent to Mr Roger Freeman, the UK defence procurement
minister, will be discussed with recommendations by a Ministry of Defence
procurement committee to buy a number of C-130J Lockheed aircraft as an
alternative to refurbishment.
BAe has made the offer because it wants the MoD to buy the European Future
Large Aircraft, for which BAe will build the wings. However, the FLA will
not become available until 2002, while the RAF argues that its Hercules
fleet will need replacement from 1996.
Thus far many MoD insiders have strongly backed replacement of half of the
60-strong ageing Lockheed Hercules with the same company's C-130J rather
than opting for refurbishment, which it had considered uneconomic.
However, the Treasury is thought to be interested in BAe's proposals, which
would not require the MoD to buy new aircraft or refurbish the existing
Hercules fleet. Both departments will be represented at the committee
meeting on Thursday, as will the Department of Trade and Industry and the
Scottish Office.
BAe has offered to maintain a fleet of 50 Hercules aircraft, 70 per cent of
which would be available at any time, at a fixed cost 20 per cent lower than
the RAF's current maintenance costs.
The company is also undertaking to complete any refurbishment work which is
needed at no cost to the RAF. BAe puts the cost of maintaining the Hercules
fleet at Pounds 52m a year.
In a separate note BAe has also suggested that the MoD sells its Hercules
fleet to BAe and leases it back to further improve the department's
finances.
The RAF is thought to have only half of its 60 Hercules available for use at
any time. It is also thought to be intending to reduce the size of the fleet
to 50 in 1996 even if its opts for replacement rather than refurbishment.
BAe's document claims that its offer would thus mean an increase in the
number of aircraft available at a lower cost.
The MoD confirmed that it had received an unsolicited approach from BAe
which it was considering. However, it could not confirm how quickly any
decision would be made. The MoD has said it intends to make a decision about
the Hercules fleet before Christmas.
In its document BAe says that its proposal will 'deliver real value for
money to the MoD and RAF while transferring risk to the private sector'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Aerospace.
