<HEADLINE>
FT  23 NOV 94 / Major attacks 'unjustifiable' salary increases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, DAVID OWEN and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major yesterday condemned 'unjustifiable' salary increases for
executives of privatised companies as Mr Cedric Brown, chief executive of
British Gas, said he was considering whether to forego part of a 75 per cent
pay rise.
The government's difficulties worsened as backbench tensions over Europe led
to an unexpected backbench challenge to Sir Marcus Fox, a key supporter of
the prime minister, for the leadership of the powerful 1922 committee of
backbench MPs.
The challenge, from Sir Nicholas Bonsor, chairman of the cross-party Commons
defence committee, was widely seen by MPs as an attempt to punish Sir Marcus
for his unswerving support for the prime minister.
In a further blow to the government, around 25 members of the Euro-sceptic
Fresh Start group last night discussed the possibility of mass abstention on
the European communities finance bill, threatening the government's majority
of 14.
The group also considered tabling an amendment to the bill, which provides
for an increase in UK contributions to the European Union. Mr Major has
threatened to call a general election if the bill is defeated or
substantially amended.
In robust Commons exchanges, Mr Major said that excessive executive pay
rises should be curbed by shareholders, but ruled out government
interference.
Mr Brown's pay rise was condemned as grotesque by Mr Tony Blair, the Labour
leader. Mr Paddy Ashdown, leader of the Liberal Democrats, said it was 'a
V-sign' to gas consumers.
Mr Blair later wrote to Mr Major urging the government to withdraw tax
privileges for executive share options and give regulators power to limit
price increases in industries subject to excessive salary rises.
Mr Brown said that he understood the reaction to the company's announcement
that his salary was to rise from Pounds 270,000 a year to Pounds 475,000. 'I
will consider my options and discuss it with my colleagues and executive
directors in the light of all that has been said,' he told Sky News.
Tory backbenchers said the battle for the leadership of the 1922 committee
could become a proxy contest between Sir Marcus and rightwingers seeking to
destabilise Mr Major's leadership.
Sir Nicholas said his challenge was 'categorically not an attack on the
prime minister'. However, backbenchers said there was a desire to rebuke Sir
Marcus for delivering a warning on behalf of the prime minister that the
defeat of the EU finance bill would prompt an election.
