<HEADLINE>
FT  23 NOV 94 / RJB seeks to cut Pounds 35m off bid for British Coal regions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH and PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RJB Mining, the coal company chosen by the government as preferred bidder
for British Coal's English regions, is seeking to shave at least Pounds 35m
off its Pounds 914m bid after finding coal stocks are below expectations.
It told institutional investors that British Coal's English stockpiles are
1.3m tonnes of coal down on when it made its bid, and this should enable it
to negotiate a Pounds 35m reduction in the purchase price.
The coal stock change provides a fillip for the company's efforts to raise
up to Pounds 1.05bn through borrowing and selling shares. RJB was given
further cheer when Mr John Jermine, executive chairman of NSM, another coal
company which bid for British Coal assets, expressed support for the bid.
Other failed bidders have attacked RJB's assumptions on future sales as
unrealistic but Mr Jermine, whose company bid unsuccessfully for the south
Wales region, said he thought the plans would work.
In City presentations, Mr Richard Budge, RJB chief executive, has told
institutional investors that the 'due diligence' process, through which it
is inspecting the assets, could produce further reductions in the price, on
top of the Pounds 35m it expects to save on coal stocks.
However, the company is not expecting cuts of more than Pounds 100m. Mr
Budge told investors there could be savings of tens of millions, not
hundreds. Government advisers are said to share that assessment.
Although the lower coal stocks will reduce the value of the regions being
acquired, they will also ease RJB's fund-raising task. It could be seeking
less than Pounds 1bn for the bid. The company is valued at just Pounds 157m
on the stock market.
In the face of strong criticism from rival bidders and analysts, Mr Budge is
presenting a highly confident face to the City.
He acknowledges that his company would fail to make the money it has
projected - Pounds 220m in pre-tax profits in 1999 alone - if coal demand at
the end of the century was as low as it has allowed in 'conservative case'
assumptions.
Those figures are viewed by some analysts as too high, but Mr Budge points
out they include forecasts that gas-fired generation will take the place of
up to 50m tonnes of coal equivalent - more than most expectations. The
figures also allow a high market share, 8.3m tonnes of coal equivalent, for
the burning of orimulsion - a bitumen-based fuel.
Mr Budge says he is also making conservative assumptions on cost-cutting, 3
per cent a year, for achieving profit projections.
He assumes, however, that coal can be sold to electricity generators at an
average of Pounds 1.25 per gigajoule after 1998 and Pounds 1.32 in 1999.
These projections, and those for sales of 34m tonnes in 1999, are seen as
extremely optimistic by rival bidders.
RJB refused to comment but Mr Budge has told institutions that at least 90
per cent of debt, possibly all of it, would be paid when existing contracts
with generators expire in April 1998.
The company is also planning to buy two pits, Ellington in Northumberland
and Thorne in Yorkshire, in addition to the 15 which are part of the three
regions it is buying.
Putting Pounds 1bn down the mines, Page 30
