<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / London Stock Exchange: Hanson bucks bad news
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and JEFFREY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Internationally traded conglomerate Hanson saw its shares ignore some
disappointing news and forge ahead as investors finally noted their recent
underperformance.
The company announced that it had been forced to drop the planned flotation
of US toy maker Ertl because of poor stock market conditions. The news put
paid to hopes that it would raise some Dollars 200m for a 63 per cent
flotation.
However, a large line of some 8m shares which had been washing around the
market was finally cleared, and several specialists pointed out that the
Hanson share price had underperformed the broad market by 7 per cent over
the past quarter.
Investment houses have been expressing their confidence ahead of full-year
figures due next Thursday. Company broker Hoare Govett was in Scotland
talking to investment institutions following a positive review and Lehman
Brothers was discussing a buy note with clients. Hanson gained 4 at 237p,
with turnover reaching 12m, the heaviest among leading issues.
</TEXT>
