<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Rate worries leave Dow
sharply lower
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA BRANSTEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
Program selling left US share prices at their lowest levels since August 22
yesterday amid uncertainty about future interest rate increases by the
Federal Reserve, writes Lisa Bransten in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 45.75 at 3,769.51.
The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 dropped 3.17 to 458.30, while
the American SE composite weakened 2.76 to 441.28 and the Nasdaq composite
fell 6.93 to 757.74. Trading volume on the New York SE came to 293m shares.
The market began drifting downwards early in the afternoon, with the effect
snowballing towards the end of the day. At one point, just before the close,
the Dow was more than 50 points off before it made a slight comeback.
One factor pushing prices down was continued uncertainty about economic
conditions. In spite of the Federal Reserve's larger than expected increase
in interest rates last week, most economists believe that the Fed will boost
rates again later this year or early in 1995. Such a move would be expected
to hurt equity prices by making borrowing more expensive and ultimately
putting pressure on corporate earnings.
Shares of several major cyclical companies showed declines yesterday. Allied
Signal retreated Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 32 1/4 , Caterpillar slipped
Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 54 7/8 , DuPont lost Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 54 3/4
and Dow Chemical was off Dollars 1 1/2 at Dollars 64 1/2 .
Conseco, the insurer, forged ahead Dollars 3 to Dollars 40 3/8 after a
proposed merger with Kemper fell apart. Kemper, which said it was still for
sale, tumbled Dollars 6 3/8 to Dollars 42 1/4 .
Chiron, the biotech company, gained Dollars 2 at Dollars 80 1/4 on news that
it had signed an agreement to form a partnership with Ciba-Geigy, the Swiss
pharmaceuticals company. Under the proposed alliance, Ciba-Geigy would pay
an unexpectedly high Dollars 117 per share for just over 37 per cent.
Major high-technology companies were mixed yesterday afternoon: Digital
Equipment gained Dollars 1 at Dollars 36 1/8 , Compaq Computer was up
Dollars  1/4 at Dollars 39 7/8 , IBM shed Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 72 7/8 ,
Texas Instruments lost Dollars  1/4 at Dollars 78 3/4 and Microsoft, which
trades on the Nasdaq, dipped Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 63 1/2 .
Hewlett-Packard lost Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 99 3/4 and Apple Computer shed
Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 38 1/8 .
Canada
Initial firmness in Toronto quickly evaporated and stocks drifted easier
before dropping sharply late in the session, dragged down by the Wall Street
trend.
The TSE 300 index finished 40.22 weaker at 4,074.31, while declines
outscored rises by 553 to 221 after volume of 40.9m shares valued at
CDollars 426.9m. All 14 sub-indices were lower, led by gold, metal, real
estate and transportation stocks.
Heavily weighted golds were the main drag on the composite index, falling
2.52 per cent as the New York spot bullion price shed 90 cents to USDollars
383.55 an ounce.
</TEXT>
<XX>
