<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / International Company News: BancOne posts loss on securities
holdings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BancOne, one of the biggest US banks, yesterday announced a one-off
after-tax loss of Dollars 170m on its securities holdings, showing the
damage done to some banks' earnings from the rise in US interest rates since
February.
The bank said the loss stemmed from the sale of Dollars 5.7bn of fixed
income securities which have an average maturity of three years.
The Columbus, Ohio-based bank had been one of the most aggressive in its use
of fixed-rate instruments to lift earnings.
BancOne had used bonds and interest rate swaps to increase its fixed-income
earnings, while keeping a large portion of its liabilities tied to floating
interest rates. The policy enabled it to report one of the best net interest
margins of any US bank last year, but led to a contraction in earnings as
rates moved against it.
Shortly before US rates began to rise in February, BancOne estimated that a
gradual 1 percentage point increase in short-term rates over the following
12 months would reduce its earnings by 3.3 per cent. In the event, rates
have risen 2 1/2 percentage points since the first increase engineered by
the Federal Reserve on February 4.
Doubts about the wisdom of BancOne's interest rate policy have hung over its
share price for more than a year. Yesterday, Mr John McCoy, chairman, said:
'We are determined to take the necessary steps in 1994 to put the issue of
interest rate sensitivity behind us.' In addition, the bank said it would
take an after-tax charge of Dollars 65m to reflect restructuring costs. The
bank indicated it expected to cut 4,300 jobs by the end of next year.
Last week PNC, a regional bank based in Pittsburgh, said a
faster-than-expected rise in interest rates would reduce its net interest
income by about 7 per cent in the final three months of this year, and 15
per cent next year.
</TEXT>
