<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Emap sets sights on European purchase: Publishing group
lifts interim profits 34% to Pounds 22m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Emap, the newspaper, magazine and exhibitions group, is 'seriously
interested' in the European publishing operations of Maclean Hunter, the
Canadian media group.
Emap, which yesterday announced a 34 per cent rise in pre-tax profits to
Pounds 22.2m for the six months to October 1, is believed to be one of five
groups bidding for the Maclean Hunter business titles in the UK and
continental Europe.
Rogers Communications, which recently acquired Maclean, is selling the
assets which are expected to raise more than Pounds 50m.
Mr David Arculus, managing director of Emap, said the company regards the
Maclean titles, which include UK Press Gazette, as a 'bolt-on' to its
existing business titles.
'Our next tranche of deals will be bolt-on deals and we are looking at quite
a number of them,' he said.
During the first half, Emap spent Pounds 197m on acquisitions including
Pounds 106m acquiring 28 magazines from the French publishers Editions
Mondiales and a further 10 consumer titles from companies within the Hersant
group of France.
The company also spent Pounds 50m on Trans World Communications with
commercial radio stations in Manchester, Preston, Leeds and Cardiff.
Emap is the second-largest player in commercial radio in the UK after
Capital with about 12 per cent of the market.
Emap said the French purchases had cost about 75p-77p for every Pounds 1 in
turnover. Margins were about 5 per cent compared with 17 per cent for its UK
consumer magazines.
The company hopes that rationalisation and better margins on distribution
will lift margins to 10 per cent within the next two to three years.
Underlying growth was 24 per cent. Turnover was 38 per cent up at Pounds
234.2m. Earnings per share rose by 31 per cent to 7.9p and the intermim at
2.5p was up by 13 per cent.
Mr Richard Dale, media analyst from stockbrokers Smith New Court, upgraded
his forecast for Emap's full-year pre-tax figure from Pounds 59m to Pounds
61m and from Pounds 76m to Pounds 79m for the 1995-96 financial year.
On the consumer magazine side, Emap said the successes were More, the
magazine for young women which put on 17 per cent in sales to 400,000, and
Match Weekly, a football magazine which increased sales by 21 per cent to
137,000. Computer games magazines were the poor performers with circulation
falls of around 30 per cent.
Mr Robin Miller, Emap chief executive, said newspaper advertising revenue
rose 11 per cent. Employment advertising rose 42 per cent, but local retail
advertising was still hit by consumer caution.
