<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Observer: Deuce
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Two years ago, SAS International Hotels came up with an acceptably ageist
wheeze. Provided there were vacancies, guests over 65 could get a discount
equivalent to their ages. So 70-year-olds had 70 per cent knocked off their
bill; anyone arriving in their hundredth year would get the room free.
Kurt Ritter, chief executive of Radisson-SAS, as the company is now called,
says all went well until a Swedish guest turned up recently at one of the
company's hostelries in Vienna and announced that he was 102. He demanded to
be paid 2 per cent of the room rate to stay the night. The hotel agreed. The
sprightly guest then demanded a game of tennis with the general manager -
and got that, too. It is not known whether he took the GM to five sets.
