<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Observer: Future imperfect
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Whoops. The Bank of England is just about to lose its top economic
forecaster. Paul Mortimer-Lee, 41, head of the Bank's economic forecasting
division, is off to be chief economist of Paribas Capital Markets in a
couple of months' time.
Most Bank economists jump ship at a much earlier stage in their careers, and
the loss of an official of Mortimer-Lee's seniority could be a bit of a blow
for the Bank. The operation of UK monetary policy depends very much on his
type of skill. Decisions on whether to raise or lower base rates are based
on a judgment of inflation 18 months to two years ahead, and the Bank has
sought to set the framework for such decisions through its quarterly
inflation reports.
Unless the Old Lady moves convincingly to plug the gap, it could find its
expertise challenged by the clever clogs at the Treasury and elsewhere.
</TEXT>
