<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Schools' League Tables: Local authorities cast doubt on the
accuracy of truancy figures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM LEWIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The accuracy of the truancy figures for England released by the government
was called into question yesterday by a number of local education
authorities.
Manchester, top of the truancy table for secondary schools and, for the
second year running, home to the 'worst' school in England, said yesterday
that up to 11,000 pupils had been omitted from the government's
calculations. A similar problem occurred last year.
The authority said nearly a third of its schools had failed to return
absenteeism figures to the government. As a result the validity of the
tables was in doubt.
The government recorded a total of 48,566 pupils of compulsory school age in
Manchester, but according to the authority the actual figure is just under
60,000.
The authority said: 'We do recognise that Manchester does have a problem
with truancy, but we are taking active steps to deal with it both within the
local education authority and on an individual school basis.
'However, the overall picture presented by the tables is very misleading.'
The authority stressed that of the 11,000 pupils not included in the table
there were 'some very good schools that would have had a very good record on
attendance'.
The local education authority for Kensington and Chelsea, placed second to
Manchester in the secondary school truancy table, also criticised the
accuracy of the government's calculations.
It said that its figure for the percentage of half days missed by secondary
school pupils without authorisation - a key truancy measure - was out by
nearly a quarter.
Kensington and Chelsea said yesterday that the correct figure was 2.8 per
cent, not 3.6 per cent as recorded in the government's table.
According to the authority the mistake was due to one of its schools having
filled in a form incorrectly. Mr Mike Stoten, head of education for
Kensington and Chelsea, said: 'The department has admitted it has got the
wrong number in its booklet, but they are being bloody-minded and are
refusing to change it.'
Officials at the Department for Education said the authority should blame
itself for not having checked through its submission properly.
An official said: 'It will certainly learn a lesson for next year.'
Tower Hamlets, another of the worst placed authorities, also suggested that
the government's figures differed from the ones its schools had submitted.
The authority said: 'These things are just so complicated it is not
surprising that cock-ups occur.'
However, most of the individual schools badly placed in the truancy league
were willing to admit to having attendance problems.
The two worst schools, Ellen Wilkinson High School in Manchester and Agnes
Stewart High School in Leeds, both recorded a truancy rate of 30 per cent.
Mrs Yvonne Kneen, headteacher of Ellen Wilkinson, said that in spite of a
number of initiatives to reduce truancy it would take a long time for the
school to solve the problem. She believes it is mainly a function of the
disadvantaged backgrounds of most of the school's pupils, who live in
inner-city Manchester.
The school has taken on a special school liaison teacher, whose role is to
check on children who have a poor attendance record. Some of the school's
governors have been involved in searching the local shopping centre for
absent pupils and the local police have been patrolling nearby streets in
unmarked cars.
</TEXT>
