<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Schools' League Tables: Colleges step up the fight on
A-level battleground
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Today's performance tables reveal significant changes in the pattern of
English education for post-16-year-olds.
Further-education colleges, for long the Cinderellas of education, appear to
be competing fiercely in the marketplace for A-level education. Following
incorporation in April last year, all colleges have been removed from local
authority control and are run as independent organisations.
They are funded in relation to their student numbers. This has given them a
strong incentive to recruit students who might at one time have gone to
schools.
Several colleges are sizeable institutions with more than 1,000 candidates
entered for different qualifications.
Many authorities also wanted to establish sixth-form colleges simply to save
money, a move recommended by the Audit Commission among others. Four local
education authorities - Richmond-upon-Thames, Salford, Bury and Harrow - no
longer have any school sixth forms and entrust all their A-level provision
to sixth-form colleges. The government only publishes local authorities'
average A-level results for schools, however, and excludes further education
colleges, so it is difficult to judge whether these policies have been
successful.
Some policymakers are worried that too many colleges now offer A-levels, and
that their traditional concentration on vocational qualifications means they
do not provide adequate academic competition for schools.
In the past year the Department for Education gave approval to several
schools catering for 11-16-year-olds to start sixth forms. Mr John Patten,
the former education secretary, had said that schools without a sixth form
were like 'a body without a head'.
The figures lend this some support, but it is only limited. Several colleges
which would be viable if they offered only vocational qualifications have
started entering significant numbers of candidates for A-levels, and several
appear to have rather weaker results than the average of all schools.
It is difficult to measure this, however, as the government is trying to
encourage a 'mixed economy' of A-levels and vocational qualifications, which
in many cases will be good for entry to new universities. Thus it is hard to
compare schools which do only A-levels with colleges where academic
qualifications are often a supplement to a much more time-consuming
vocational course.
The Department for Education's tables tackle these problems by quoting the
average Ucas points for candidates who attempt two or more A-levels, and for
those who attempt one. The idea is to separate those taking an A-level to
top up a vocational course from students taking a fully academic course,
therefore providing a fairer comparison.
Candidates trying two or more A-levels at colleges - and therefore making
A-level the backbone of their courses - fared less well at further-education
colleges, but the gap was small. According to government data, the average
points score in schools was 16.7, but when all further education colleges
were included, this fell to 15.3.
The table lists the 20 colleges which offered the most vocational
qualifications, and in most cases they also offered sizeable numbers of
wholly A-level courses. In most of the cases listed A-level performance was
significantly below average.
However, many of the colleges, such as Sheffield, enter large numbers of
candidates, making it much harder to maintain a high average.
Calculations for Colchester Sixth-Form College (pictured), which last year
entered 678 A-level candidates, demonstrate the distortions large numbers of
entrants can cause. The college's most successful 100 candidates this year
gained an average of 33.07 Ucas points, a score which would have ranked them
in the top five for the country, among selective schools which have about
100 pupils per year.
</TEXT>
