<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Schools' League Tables: Grant-maintained schools spending
plans exaggerated by 40 per cent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The cross-party Commons education select committee yesterday said the
Department for Education's spending plans for grant-maintained schools which
have opted out of local authority control had been exaggerated by 40 per
cent, John Authers writes.
It said the figures were 'inconsistent and implausible' and risked
undermining education expenditure planning.
Early last year the department predicted that by January this year there
would be 700,000 pupils in grant-maintained schools, with 1m by April this
year. But instead the number of schools opting out has subsided and only
550,000 pupils were taught in the sector by the start of this year, 600,000
in April and 620,000 by October.
It meant that by April the number of pupils in grant-maintained schools was
40 per cent below the level planned for by the government.
The MPs said the department's spending projections suggested either that
growth would have to be reduced or that there was a 'systematic
understatement' of what was happening. They dismissed officials' claims that
the figures were not predictions but 'working assumptions'.
The report said: 'Semantic fine-tuning cannot hide the fact that the
department's projections for grant-maintained pupils numbers have proved
very inaccurate.
'If it were to turn out that many more of the government's plans were merely
working assumptions with no real substance, the whole basis of the public
expenditure planning process could be jeopardised.'
The committee's comments come as a further blow to ministers who are
campaigning to encourage schools to opt out. Labour has said that
grant-maintained schools would be returned to some form of 'local democratic
accountability' which has further curbed the numbers opting out.
It added that the department had to 'improve its quality control'.
</TEXT>
