<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Schools' League Tables: On-line reports to parents urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Parents could be given on-line computer access to school inspectors' reports
and other information collected by Ofsted, the schools watchdog, under
proposals outlined yesterday.
Mr Mark Gladwyn, head of strategic programmes at CCTA, the government centre
for information systems, suggested that the information collected and held
by Ofsted might be made available to personal computer users over the
Internet - the informal system of computer networks which connects databases
and computers across the globe.
Mr Gladwyn said the records of births, deaths and marriages since 1837 could
also be made available on-line - a move which he said would be immensely
valuable to historians and other researchers.
Earlier this month the Treasury confirmed that Mr Kenneth Clarke's Budget
speech would be made available over the Internet soon after the chancellor
delivered it to the Commons next Tuesday.
'Information superhighways present us with a new and exciting opportunity to
improve the way we share and access information,' Mr Gladwyn said yesterday.
He was speaking at a CCTA consultative meeting on information superhighways
attended by more than 800 public and private sector delegates.
He said providing electronic access to information was in line with the
government's drive for more open government. The Open Government Code of
Practice, published earlier this year, emphasised the importance of
volunteering and increasing the availability and accessibility of government
information.
Mr Robert Hughes, minister for public service and science, said the
information superhighway 'means government is open for business around the
clock. The individual citizen can ask questions when it suits them, their
school or small business rather than when it suits a civil servant.'
</TEXT>
