<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Schools' League Tables: Catchment area link to success is
underlined
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The list of England's strongest and weakest non-selective schools at GCSE
demonstrates the powerful link between a school's success and the catchment
area from which it draws children.
At the top of the table are comprehensives which tend to be based in wealthy
suburban areas, such as Bexley Grammar in south London or George Abbot near
Guildford, Surrey, or to have a well-established reputation so that they are
over-subscribed, and therefore to some degree selective.
Hasmonean High in north London, which has developed a nationwide reputation
since newspapers started publishing league tables based on exam results, has
again ranked highly on GCSE scores. It has a distinctive ethos because it is
a Jewish school catering for the north London Jewish community, and cannot
be described as a typical neighbourhood comprehensive.
Several others have 'grammar school' in their name, indicating past
traditions, although they are now non-selective.
The lowest achievers at GCSE virtually all fall in urban areas and most are
shown as having high truancy rates.
Schools which the Department for Education listed as achieving five GCSE
grade Cs for less than 10 per cent of their pupils are in a series of inner
urban areas. They include: Grange Upper and Belle Vue Boys in Bradford;
Broadgreen, Croxteth and John Paul II Roman Catholic High in Liverpool;
Malory in London; George Dixon GM in Birmingham; Lyndhurst in Gateshead; and
the Benjamin Gott High School in Leeds.
Most are still maintained by their local education authority but a number of
schools which have special status as part of government initiatives to
revitalise education in inner cities are also among the lowest performers.
For example no pupils achieved five GCSE grade Cs or better at Battersea
Technology College in Wandsworth, south London, which specialises in
technology.
Some are near much more successful schools, leading to the claim that
selective schools in big cities, often believed to have offered social
mobility to able children from deprived backgrounds, have helped ensure
other urban schools are even less successful.
For example in Liverpool, the Blue Coat school, a comprehensive with
long-rooted independent traditions and one of the highest GCSE pass-rates in
the country, co-exists with several of the weakest performers.
Three Birmingham schools appear in the bottom 50 in spite of the presence in
the city of King Edward's and King Edward VI independent schools, which
offer state assistance to children through the government's assisted places
scheme, and several grammar schools. The city ranks 85th overall among
English education authorities, slightly better than its level of social
deprivation might indicate.
Value-added studies by academics suggest that pupils at all levels of
ability perform better in exams if the children surrounding them are more
able. This is usually taken as an argument for selectivity, but as
researchers such as Mr Peter Tymms of the University of Newcastle put it in
a recent study, the finding could lead to two separate policies: 'Does it
make sense to separate out the very able so that they can feed,
intellectually, on one another or should their beneficial influence be as
widely spread as possible?'
The presence of many big independent day schools in London may also have
speeded 'middle-class flight', hitting inner-city comprehensives.
Only 11 per cent of pupils managed the equivalent of five O-levels at
Highbury Grove in Islington, north London, where Sir Rhodes Boyson, the
former Conservative education minister, was once headmaster. It serves an
area hit hard by social deprivation, but many parents in the borough's
pockets of affluence may have opted out of the state system.
Mr David Blunkett, the Labour education spokesman, yesterday seized on these
figures, promising action to deal with inner-city 'sink' schools. He said:
'Where we will do much more than this government is by acting to help those
schools which are falling behind, to prevent them from becoming sink
schools.'
He added action was crucial in primary schools, if under-achievement at
secondary schools was to be stopped.
</TEXT>
<XX>
