<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Schools' League Tables: Wales 'long way short of targets'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
All eight counties in Wales have shown an improvement this year in the
average performance of pupils at state schools in obtaining GCSE passes. But
Mr John Redwood, Welsh secretary, said the results left Wales still behind
England and Scotland and 'a long way short of our targets'.
He said he was pleased that 136 maintained schools had recorded an
improvement in the number of pupils achieving five or more A-C grades and
that the Welsh average had improved from 37 per cent to 39 per cent.
He added, however: 'The spread of results, with the best LEA school
obtaining 73 per cent and the worst only 4 per cent, is far too wide. More
action is needed to lift standards in the worst performing schools.'
Average performance ranged from 30 per cent of pupils gaining five or more
A-C grades in Mid Glamorgan to 45 per cent in Dyfed and Powys. The biggest
improvements were in South Glamorgan, which went from 35 per cent last year
to 40 per cent, and in Powys, which was up from 40 per cent.
The highest-scoring state school - with 73 per cent of pupils gaining five
or more A-C grades - was Bishop of Llandaff High School in Cardiff. The
worst performing, with 4 per cent, was Glan Ely High School in Cardiff.
Among independent schools Westbourne College gained a 100 per cent figure,
and Howell's School 99 per cent. Both are in South Glamorgan.
More than 19 out of 20 state pupils aged 15 were entered for at least one
GCSE or Certificate of Education this year, and nine out of 10 pupils gained
one or more graded GCSE result.
At A/AS-level all counties but one showed an improvement in the average
passes of candidates entered for two or more subjects. The exception was
Gwynedd, which on a points basis stayed at 14, the same level as last year.
The average for Welsh schools rose from 14 to 15.
The range was from 13 points in Mid Glamorgan to 16 in Powys and South
Glamorgan.
The highest rating by a state school was by Penglais Comprehensive,
Aberystwyth, with an average per pupil of 23 points for those taking two or
more subjects. In the independent sector Ffynone House School in West
Glamorgan scored best with 28 points.
This year the Welsh Office publishes the absenteeism level at schools. Mr
Redwood said: 'I recognise that irregular attendance in many cases might be
out of the immediate control of the school. But I hope by publishing these
figures it will encourage schools to investigate unauthorised absences.
'I find it very worrying that in Mid Glamorgan pupils on average miss more
than one day a fortnight, and in South Glamorgan more than one fifth of all
the absences are unauthorised.'
</TEXT>
