<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Schools' League Tables: Scotland reports steady improvement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The tables of examination results for Scottish schools show a small but
steady improvement over the past three years in the performance of pupils in
Standard grade, the exam taken by those aged 14 and 15.
There was also a modest improvement in highers, the main examination for
school leavers entering further and higher education.
The tables, covering 1992-93, also show that schools in Orkney, followed by
Shetland, have the best performance in standard grade and in highers,
followed by the Western Isles and Borders region. Strathclyde region has the
worst performance, with the average of seven areas in the region dragged
down by one of them, Glasgow.
The Scottish Office does not provide a league table of schools, nor does it
give the truancy rate. This is because Scottish Office ministers concluded
that to present results as a league table would be misleading because it
would not take account of individual schools' intake and the economic and
social background of their catchment area.
The Scottish Office believed truancy figures were likely to be misleading.
The tables, produced by the audit unit of HM Inspectors of Schools, contains
11 measures of performance for each secondary school, covering the numbers
of presentations and the grades achieved in standard grades, highers,
certificate of sixth-form studies and vocational certificate modules.
The tables also list the performance of private schools in Scottish
examinations. This does not usually present a full picture of those schools,
because they normally enter pupils for English GCSEs and A-levels, as do a
small number of state schools.
A leading figure in Scottish education said: 'The best way for parents to
use these tables is to study the performance of the school their child is
attending, or will be attending. Unless they know the background against
which other schools operate comparisons are virtually meaningless.'
The tables show that over the three years a slightly higher percentage of
pupils achieved better levels in standard grade, and there was a modest
increase in the percentage of pupils gaining one or more higher in bands A
to C, the top three bands.
Lord James Douglas-Hamilton MP, the Scottish Office education minister, said
the government would be studying a way of measuring the value added to
pupils by each school.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
