<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Schools' League Tables: GCSE yardstick shows 5% boost -
Figures for A-levels reveal 4% improvement / Selective independents continue
their dominance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For the second year running the Department for Education performance tables
of English schools show sharp improvements in GCSE and A-level exams.
In the most closely monitored indicators, schools logged a 5.35 per cent
improvement in the numbers passing at least five GCSE exams at grade C or
better. The performance of pupils taking mainly A-levels in the sixth form
improved by 4 per cent.
The national average was for 43.3 per cent of a school's pupils to achieve
at least five C grades at GCSE, while 85.6 per cent achieved five at the
lower grade of G.
Candidates for two A-levels or more managed a score of 16.7 Ucas points on
average, a 4 per cent improvement from 1993.
These figures, following an improvement of 8 per cent in GCSE performance
last year, fuelled claims that schools' behaviour had been changed by the
tables.
The government now seems likely to publish new indicators next year,
however. There has been renewed criticism that the tables do not put
schools' performance in sufficient context to make sound judgment.
That criticism is made on two grounds: that the tables exclude measures of
pupils' ability when they started at school, and that they omit social and
economic problems in a school's catchment area.
The Labour party and Labour-led local authority associations back
publication of such measures. They now approve of league tables in
principle, although they object to the way the government has chosen to
present the information.
Independent schools have continued their dominance, accounting for all but
four of the top schools in the A-level league and almost three quarters of
the 200 judged by their GCSE results.
Figures for vocational qualifications taken by 16-year-olds gave support to
the government's decision to introduce new, more rigorous General National
Vocational Qualifications in schools next year. The national average pass
rate in schools which offered vocational qualifications to 16-year-olds was
87.6 per cent.
Local authorities, having abandoned their opposition to the tables, said
more information rather than less should be published. This was partly
because of the continued powerful correlation between social deprivation and
poor scores in GCSE exams.
As last year the Financial Times has included an indicator of social
deprivation to put local authorities' performance into context. This is
taken from the Additional Educational Needs index, which until last year was
used by the environment department as part of its calculations for
distributing grants to councils.
This index was calculated using three factors: the proportion of benefit
claimants in an area, the proportion of children from single-parent
families, and the proportion of immigrants (an indication of the number of
children who do not speak English as a first language). It has been
discontinued, but local authority associations believe the index as updated
last year provides a fair reflection of the social problems faced by
different authorities.
As happened last year, the authorities with the most additional educational
needs had the weakest GCSE results. Southwark in London, bottom for the
second year in three, ranked 102nd of the 108 authorities in England which
administer secondary schools for social deprivation. All the authorities in
the bottom 10 by GCSE performance were in the bottom 20 judged by
deprivation.
It appears difficult for individual local education authorities to shift
more than a few places in the overall tables from year to year. Only 12
authorities moved by more than 10 places compared with last year.
The Isles of Scilly's one secondary school has children up to the age of 16
and has negligible truancy. It is top for the third year running and is
likely to remain so.
The rest of the upper reaches are dominated by outer-London boroughs, whose
problems tend to be overstated by the index of additional educational needs,
and by counties in the south-east.
The Labour-controlled Association of London Authorities, whose members
include several of the worst-performing authorities at GCSE, said the
government should have included a measure of schools' improvement.
It published its own figures, compiled by Keele University, for 75 London
schools, mapping their performance since 1990, when the Inner London
Education Authority was abolished and control of education was given to the
inner London boroughs.
This used an index for GCSE performance with the 1990 level taken as 100. On
this basis only one school failed to improve since 1990 while five had more
than doubled their performance.
Ms Sheila Knight, who chairs the association's education committee, said the
tables 'can lead to complacency in those schools which are apparently doing
well, and demoralisation in those schools which are working desperately hard
to improve the results of less able pupils'. She called for a measure of
schools' improvement to be included.
The School Curriculum and Assessment Authority is expected to publish its
proposals for showing the value which schools have added to pupils next
week. They are expected to endorse a measure similar to that used by the
association.
The Association of Metropolitan Authorities, also Labour-controlled, backed
publishing more information rather than less, and said the job could be done
more cheaply by the authorities themselves.
</TEXT>
<XX>
