<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Budget 1994: Sizing up the chancellor's shade of green - The
environmental options business and lobbyists would like to see in the Budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The caution with which environmental pressure groups, manufacturers and
retailers greeted the proposed pollution measures announced in last week's
Queen's Speech was typical of the wariness surrounding government attempts
to 'green' domestic and business activities.
They are now wondering whether Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, will
include measures intended to help the environment in his Budget next week.
Business is concerned about how fiscal instruments will affect
competitiveness. Pressure groups fear taxation could be used to replace
regulatory measures.
Most groups expect the chancellor to continue raising duty on fuel. Mr Roger
Bate, director of the environment unit at the Institute of Economic Affairs,
said: 'He is committed to a 5 per cent real increase per annum on fuel . . .
There was quite a lot of bad press on VAT on domestic fuel but now that is
considered water under the bridge so my guess is that will probably stay.'
Some analysts argue that increasing fuel prices - especially for cars - may
make little or no impact on pollution. Mr John Cridland, environment
director of the Confederation of British Industry, said: 'It has not been
demonstrated that increasing the price on petrol would reduce the cars on
the road.'
Mr Bate warned that fuel taxes bore most heavily on those who were least
responsible for the problem. 'The worst effects are on disparate groups,
like rural individuals who contribute very little to pollution. It would be
better to privatise the roads or introduce congestion pricing,' he said.
Alternative options for addressing this problem would need a longer
timescale than one Budget and would entail considerable capital investment.
One such option might be congestion pricing - taxing car owners based on the
amount of time they spend in traffic jams - to target the environmental
problem directly, rather than taxing activities associated with
environmental damage, such as the use of fuel.
Such a charge would require cars to be fitted with a smart card that would
tally the minutes spent idling in traffic, with the owner charged
accordingly, encouraging drivers to travel at different times or to use
public transport.
The Institute for Fiscal Studies, which produced a prospectus for possible
inclusions in the Budget, discussed one mechanism for direct taxation of
pollution: emission taxation on individual sources. Units of pollution would
be measured much like gas or electricity use, and taxed proportionately.
The institute said there was a trade-off between direct taxes such as
emission taxation, and financial instruments based on existing tax bases -
such as VAT on fuel. Setting up a new tax system might entail high
administrative costs, but is more likely to be specifically levied on
sources of pollution.
In the Queen's Speech the government made clear its plans to push through
schemes to increase recycling. One instrument that could encourage this is a
landfill levy - a charge on landfill owners in the hope that the extra cost
would be passed on to customers, encouraging them to seek other
alternatives.
The CBI supports a charge on the packaging industry to support recycling but
is sceptical about the landfill levy. Mr Cridland said: 'No analysis has
been done with the landfill levy to assess the effect it will have on
business or the environment.'
With all green taxation issues, he said, it was important to consider
whether the benefit of a particular tax to the environment outweighed the
impact on business competitiveness.
He said: 'Economic instruments are a very trendy policy mechanism but their
introduction does not always follow a thorough assessment of whether the
cost will outweigh the benefit.'
Friends of the Earth believes cost-benefit analyses should be subservient to
the need to prevent pollution at source. Mr Andrew Lees, campaign director,
said: 'A cost-benefit analysis in the traditional approach is an
inappropriate tool for assessment . . . How do you do a cost benefit
analysis on the basis of value for money today versus value for money later?
Environmental assets increase with time.'
While Friends of the Earth advocates the use of taxation to curb
environmental damage, it does not believe taxation can eliminate the
problems on its own.
Mr Lees said: 'Economic instruments can only be used for fine-tuning, they
are no substitute for the regulatory approach. The government may use
environmental taxes to camouflage its deregulated agenda.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
