<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Benn expelled from MPs' sleaze inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Benn, the veteran leftwing Labour MP, was last night voted off the
Commons committee on privileges which is investigating allegations of sleaze
against two Conservative MPs.
The decision to remove Mr Benn was taken by the 17 MPs on the committee
after the former Labour cabinet minister broke its rules and gave the press
an account of the discussions at its last meeting.
The decision was taken after a session lasting 1 1/2 hours, and will be
debated in the Commons - possibly later this week. The Labour MP can only be
formally removed after a vote by the entire House.
Mr Tony Newton, the leader of the Commons and chairman of the committee,
said after the meeting: 'The committee has met and agreed a report to the
House recommending Mr Benn be removed from the committee forthwith. The
report, together with the minutes of the proceedings relating to the
committee, will be published as soon as possible.'
Mr Benn later released his own report of the committee's proceedings and the
background to the meeting.
It is understood that only two MPs - Mr Bill Michie, the MP for Sheffield
Heeley, and Mr Benn himself - voted against the expulsion. One Labour
committee member said that he backed the principle of opening some committee
sessions to the public but Mr Benn's policy of giving the press a full
account of private sessions could not be justified.
The committee is due to interview two Conservative MPs, Mr Graham Riddick
and Mr David Tredinnick, in the next few weeks after allegations that they
received cash for asking parliamentary questions.
It is also expected to probe allegations that two former ministers, Mr Neil
Hamilton and Mr Tim Smith, took payments from Mr Mohamed Fayed, the chairman
of Harrods, for tabling questions.
The committee has been in deadlock since last month when Labour MPs,
including Mr Benn, withdrew from its proceedings over a decision to hold the
inquiry in camera.
Labour MPs have insisted that justice must be seen to be done in the
'cash-for-questions' affair. But Tory MPs have expressed fears that a public
session - which could be reported under the protection of 'parliamentary
privilege' - would be unfair to interviewees.
After its last session on November 1 Mr Benn published the committee's
private deliberations as 'my own reports of its proceedings'. His account of
the meeting showed that the Conservative members argued strongly against
interviewing Mr Riddick and Mr Tredinnick as long as Mr Benn insisted on
publication.
A motion expelling the MP could be put to the Commons later this week. The
committee will decide under what conditions it will interview the two Tory
MPs after the expulsion has been debated.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
</IN>
