<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Unsafe factory ships detained
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sixteen foreign ships, including five Bulgarian fish factory vessels or
'Klondykers', were detained in UK ports last month after failing safety
inspections, the Department of Transport said yesterday, Charles Batchelor
writes.
Evidence of a crackdown on fish factory ships came less than three weeks
after the government announced a series of other measures to tighten
controls because of the poor levels of maintenance on these vessels. From
next year Klondykers will have to apply in advance for licences to operate
in British waters.
Many governments have started to institute tougher controls of vessels
entering their ports because of growing dissatisfaction with the quality of
supervision exercised by the states under whose flags the vessels sail.
The five detained vessels, all flying the Bulgarian flag and owned by the
Bulgarian company Okeanski Ribolov, revealed a catalogue of deficiencies.
They were infested with cockroaches or rodents, had unhygienic accommodation
and had inadequately qualified crews.
</TEXT>
