<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Hamilton repeats Fayed denials
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Neil Hamilton, the former corporate affairs minister, last night denied
that he had been guilty of any impropriety as a result of his involvement
with Mr Mohamed Fayed, the owner of Harrods.
In his first speech in the Commons since returning to the back benches, Mr
Hamilton attacked the press for hounding him out of office after he had been
subjected to allegations.
He insisted that there was no truth in the claim that, before becoming a
minister, he had accepted bribes at 'Pounds 2,000 a time' to put down
parliamentary questions.
Nor, said Mr Hamilton, had he received Pounds 50,000 for putting down 17
questions for the House of Fraser, the one-time owner of Harrods.
Tory backbenchers rallied to his support as he denied abusing his position
as an MP, or betraying the trust of the prime minister.
Mr Hamilton said he bitterly resented suggestions that 'I was prepared to to
accept payment in cash or kind to ask parliamentary questions or change my
opinions'.
He contrasted the extended publicity given to his 'celebrated stay' at the
Ritz hotel in Paris - owned by Mr Fayed - to the brevity of a report about a
payment which Lord Callaghan, the former Labour prime minister, had failed
to declare in the Commons register of interests through a 'mere technical
over-sight'.
Mr Hamilton dismissed charges of 'so-called sleaze' levelled at the
government in general, and stressed that the 'plethora of allegations' to
which he had been subjected in no way concerned his conduct as a minister.
He suggested that the Nolan committee examining the standards of conduct in
public life should have its remit extended to cover the activities of the
media. Mr Hamilton said the power of an editor vastly transcended that of
most MPs and that of many ministers.
</TEXT>
