<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Litigation against coastguard rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The coastguard service cannot be sued for negligence over the way its staff
perform their normal duties, a High Court judge ruled yesterday.
Claims for damages against the service, controlled by the Department of
Transport, would be against the public interest because its efficiency and
the trust between it and the sea-going community could be damaged, Judge
Gareth Edwards QC said.
He dismissed claims for negligence against the service which alleged
coastguards had failed to respond promptly to the distress calls on
September 5 1988 of fishing boat Inspire, which sank off the Welsh coast
with the loss of three lives.
The claims were made by Mr Sam Skinner, sole survivor of the incident, who
suffered post-traumatic stress disorder after his ordeal, and the widow of
crew member David Webster.
Mr Skinner and Mr Webster's widow sued the Department of Transport, claiming
that coastguards should have acted on Mr Skinner's Mayday distress call at
3.20pm that day - heard very indistinctly by a radio operator - instead of
waiting until the boat was reported overdue at 10.30pm.
The judge ruled that coastguards owed no legally enforceable duty of care to
any member of the seafaring community - even in emergencies - except when
the danger was created by their own actions.
'The coastguard has vast responsibilities and slender resources,' he said.
'Litigation could involve examination of operational decisions made at a
time when an officer had to choose swiftly between several options.'
The threat of legal action was unlikely to prompt higher standards, but
might lead to a 'defensive mentality' and a drop in the effectiveness of the
service.
The judge added that he doubted whether many seafarers would wish their
relationship with the coastguard to be soured by the possibility of
litigation.
He noted that the widow of Mr Terry Jones, skipper of the boat, did not
pursue a damages claim, and said it was possible that Mr Skinner, who owed
his life to the coastguards, initially took the same view.
But Mr Skinner's psychologist had encouraged him to bring the legal action
because a finding of blame against someone might have helped him recover
from his trauma.
The judge went on: 'Speaking for myself, I wish to advise those who believe
in therapy by litigation to think again.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
