<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Labour presses for regulation of gas salaries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Labour party is to try to extend the role of the gas industry's
regulatory regime to cover excessive salary increases for top executives.
Mr Jack Cunningham, shadow trade and industry secretary, told the Commons
last night in the resumed debate on the Queen's Speech that Labour would try
to provide the additional powers through an amendment to the government bill
to increase competition in the gas industry.
He underlined the challenge the amendment would provide for Conservative
backbenchers who had criticised the 75 per cent salary rise - to Pounds
475,000 - for Mr Cedric Brown, chief executive of British Gas.
He said the salary increases were a 'scandal' and condemned Mr Michael
Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, for lacking the courage to
oppose them.
Mr Heseltine insisted that since privatisation British Gas had improved its
competitiveness and profitability.
He told jeering Labour MPs that it was the success of the government's
privatisation policy that had forced them to abandon threats of
re-nationalisation.
Mr Heseltine recalled that Mr John Major, the prime minister, had stressed
that the government believed it was necessary for executives to exercise
'restraint' in awarding salary increases. Such increases would also be
subject to judgment by the market and by shareholders.
Downing Street said, however, that although Mr Major would not comment on
the particular case of British Gas, he felt 'very strongly' about excessive
pay rises.
A spokesman said that if shareholders in a private company felt pay rises
were excessive, they could take action to curb them.
Mr Jeremy Hanley, the Conservative party chairman, added his voice to
criticisms of the pay shake-up when he told Channel 4 News: 'I think that it
is insensitive and there is no doubt at all that there will be much
criticism of that decision.'
Meanwhile, Mr Brown yesterday insisted he would have earned Pounds 400,000
under his old pay deal, which included bonuses. Now he will just receive the
basic pay.
He added: 'I have got nothing to do with setting my salary at all.
Non-executive directors decide what they think is fair remuneration; they
decide my salary.'
</TEXT>
