<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Tories support sentiments of strategy paper
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Conservative backbenchers representing a range of views in the party
yesterday voiced support for the main thrust of a strategy paper written by
Mr John Maples, the deputy chairman, and obtained by the Financial Times.
Sir Nicholas Bonsor, chairman of the Commons defence committee, said he
agreed with most of the sentiments in Mr Maples's paper. 'It is not the
policy itself. It is the way the policies are put over. Our policies are not
being explained properly. What he said - although it was lurid language -
was something most of us would agree with.'
Mr Cyril Townsend, MP for Bexleyheath, said Mr Maples had hit 'a number of
nails on the head' and produced the sort of document the leadership needed.
'I don't agree with all his comments, but I think he was absolutely right to
give the advice he did in general.'
Mr John Townend, rightwing chairman of the Tory backbench finance committee,
said he had been pressing ministers to wake up to reality for some time.
Mr David Shaw, MP for Dover, said: 'The broad thrust of what John has said
is absolutely right. It closely accords with what people have been saying
inside the party.'
Mr Richard Shepherd, the Eurosceptic MP for Aldridge Brownhills, said the
memorandum 'has effectively been written to the government by every
Conservative MP over the last year'.
Several MPs said Mr Maples accurately reflected their belief that Mr Kenneth
Clarke, the chancellor, should postpone the next increase in value added tax
on fuel due next April.
Labour, which yesterday submitted a petition to 10 Downing Street opposing
the increase from 8 per cent to 17.5 per cent, is to try to force a vote
blocking it after next week's Budget.
Mr Clarke is thought to be determined to press on with the increase. He is
thought to believe that postponing it would merely add to the government's
difficulties by allowing Labour to prolong its attacks on the issue.
Mr Tony Blair, Labour leader, said it was 'significant' that the document
admitted 'on the key areas of concern to the voters - the economy, living
standards, NHS, social division - we are getting it right and they are
getting it wrong'.
Commenting on Mr Maples's suggestion that a few backbench 'yobbos' should
metaphorically beat him up, Mr Blair said he was not particularly surprised:
'Character assassination is their stock-in-trade.'
</TEXT>
