<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Call for return of cash from IRA raid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELFAST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Patrick Mayhew, Northern Ireland secretary, yesterday called on the IRA
to return the money stolen in a post office raid in Newry on November 10,
during which postal worker Mr Frank Kerr was killed.
Sir Patrick, speaking in Belfast after the organisation's admission of
responsibility for the robbery, said that the IRA 'cannot bring back the
life of Mr Kerr but they can mark their sincerity by returning the money
they stole'.
It is thought that Pounds 130,000 was taken in the raid.
The IRA said its members killed Mr Kerr but the robbery had not been
sanctioned by the leadership.
'Responsibility . . . for this incident lies with an identified problem in
the army's chain of command and not with the volunteers involved. This has
now been rectified,' it said in a statement.
The IRA remained committed to the peace process, the statement added. Asked
whether the IRA admission of guilt would damage plans for exploratory talks
between British officials and Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA,
before Christmas, Sir Patrick said: 'It is important that whether the attack
in Newry took place or not, the timetable laid down by the prime minister
should be adhered to.'
Sir Patrick added, however, that Mr John Major, the prime minister, had made
an important qualification for the talks, that the IRA ceasefire was
permanent.
Northern Ireland officials said yesterday talks were still most likely
before Christmas, although reports they could take place in 10 days' time
are probably premature.
Meanwhile, the implications of the IRA admission over Mr Kerr will be
considered by the Irish Republic's caretaker government today. Acting
justice minister Ms Maire Geoghegan-Quinn will report to a scheduled meeting
of the cabinet.
</TEXT>
