<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / New canvas
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Tate Gallery director Nicholas Serota contemplates the interior of the old
Bankside power station in London yesterday. The disused building, across the
Thames from St Paul's Cathedral, is to be converted into the new Tate
Gallery of Modern Art.
The final shortlist of architects for the Pounds 80m project was announced
yesterday. Just one is from the UK - David Chipperfield Architects. The
others are Herzog &amp; de Meuron (Switzerland), Office for Metropolitan
Architecture (Netherlands), Rafael Moneo (Spain), Renzo Piano Building
Workshop (Italy) and Tadao Ando Architect and Associates (Japan).
The six were chosen from an initial shortlist of 13. The winner will be
announced in February, with the building work due to begin in 1996. The
gallery, which will be bigger than the whole of the Tate's Millbank
building, is planned to open in the year 2000.
