<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Data office reacts on TV claims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBYN CHALMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tougher measures to curb the sale of confidential financial information are
being consdiered by the Office of the Data Protection Registrar following
claims that personal information about British Telecommunications' customers
is available on the black market.
A Welsh language current affairs programme, The World on 4, revealed last
night that itemised phone bills could be acquired on the black market, with
details of bank and building society accounts and national insurance
payments.
Mrs Elizabeth France, the registrar of data protection, said yesterday her
office was aware of such undertakings and was looking into ways to take
strong action against offenders.
She said: 'Recent changes approved to the criminal justice and public order
bill will only come into force in January, and we are investigating how this
will affect our powers. The sale of confidential data is of major concern to
us, and we have held talks with British Telecom and other organisations on
this issue.'
BT said there may have been instances where personnel had given out
confidential information. It said: 'In the unlikely event of a British
Telecom employee giving or selling this information, the minimum penalty
would be dismissal.'
BT viewed the issue very seriously, but did not believe it to be a
widespread problem.
</TEXT>
