<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Granada warned on breach of code
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Granada Television faces the prospect of a fine or an on-screen apology for
repeated violations of Independent Television rules on 'undue prominence' of
products in programmes.
The programme complained of is This Morning, the two-hour live, weekday ITV
programme which appears 32 weeks of the year.
Sir George Russell, Independent Television Commission chairman, has informed
Granada that the commission is 'minded to impose a statutory sanction' for
the latest two breaches of the programme and sponsorship codes.
The ITC can impose a fine of up to 3 per cent of Granada's qualifying
revenue in the last financial year or Pounds 150m.
The ITV company has been given a formal warning for an item transmitted on
September 21 which featured Mr Victor Kiam discussing his Lady Remington
range of jewellery. Viewers were invited to win pieces by devising an
advertising slogan for the range.
This, the ITC said yesterday, broke the rules which state that competition
questions must not refer directly or indirectly to the products of the prize
provider. Prizes should not be referred to editorially elsewhere in the
programme. The product was also given undue prominence during the course of
the programme.
On October 12 groceries from the Safeway supermarket group were featured as
competition prizes, the ITC says, again in breach of the rules.
The ITC said yesterday it was concerned by the recurrence of code breaches
on This Morning after six previous interventions during this year and last.
The commission said yesterday: 'The ITC considers the failure to secure
consistent compliance is unacceptable, particularly where advertiser or
product references are involved.'
Ms Andrea Wonfor, joint managing director of Granada Television, said last
night that the complaints 'represent isolated lapses in editorial judgment
but nevertheless we view breaches of the programme code extremely
seriously'.
Granada has now introduced new procedures.
</TEXT>
