<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Luanda warns over attack
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUSAKA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Angola's government accused Unita rebels of attacking its positions
yesterday and said the raids jeopardised a peace pact signed only 24 hours
earlier. State radio quoted a government statement as saying the rebels had
attacked the northern town of Uige on the eve of a permanent ceasefire which
is scheduled to be implemented at 12.00 GMT today.
Government forces captured Uige from Unita last week in what the rebels said
at the time was a violation of a truce aimed at paving the way for the peace
pact. Delegations from both sides signed the pact in the Zambian capital of
Lusaka on Sunday. But the ceremony was undermined by the failure of
President Jose Eduardo dos Santos and Unita leader Jonas Savimbi to sign it
personally, as originally planned.
