<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Russian officials blamed over cash probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An international investigation into the flight of capital from the former
Soviet Union has run into the ground because of the refusal of Russian
officials to co-operate, it was claimed yesterday.
Mr Jules Kroll, president of Kroll Associates, the leading international
corporate investigative agency, described the Russian investigation as the
'most frustrating case' of his company's 22-year history. He told UK
regulators attending a seminar in London that Russian security officials had
held back from providing information that would have allowed his agency to
name and locate those responsible for illegally transferring funds to the
west.
'We never received any feedback from their (Russian) internal security
people to whom we entrusted the task of following up our leads,' Mr Kroll
said.
This is the first time that Kroll Associates have publicly commented on the
problems of one of their most prestigious and high profile investigations.
It is estimated that the apparent failure of the Russians to complete the
contract may have cost Kroll up to Dollars 4.7m in expected revenue.
The agency was contracted amid wide publicity in 1992 by the then Russian
government led by Mr Yegor Gaidar, who is now the leader of the reformist
opposition party Russia's Choice.
The Kroll investigation had strong support from the International Monetary
Fund and the Group of Seven leading industrialised countries who were
considering fresh aid for Russia at the time but were anxious about the
issue of flight capital estimated to be running at Dollars 1bn.
Mr Kroll told the seminar organised by a London-based financial think-tank,
the Centre for the Study of Financial Innovation, that his investigators had
identified a series of suspect bank accounts and property holdings owned by
Russians in the west.
'Unfortunately we came up against a roadblock,' he said.
</TEXT>
