<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Exam results improving, league tables show
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS and WILLIAM LEWIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The number of pupils gaining five good passes in GCSE exams has increased by
more than 5 per cent for the second year running, according to government
league tables of school performance published today.
However, a Financial Times analysis showed, also for the second year
running, a strong correlation between poor GCSE pass rates and social
deprivation.
The Isles of Scilly, the least deprived area of the country according to
government indices, was first in the tables for the third year, while
Southwark, an inner London borough, had the worst results for the second
time.
Mrs Gillian Shephard, the education secretary, said the results of the
exams, taken by most 16-year-olds in England and Wales, showed the success
of the government's league tables, first published in 1992. 'This is the
foundation of a national treasure trove of information.' She said the
percentage of pupils gaining five or more GCSEs at a grade C (equivalent to
an old O-level pass) or better rose from 38.3 per cent in 1992, when the
tables were first published, to 41.1 per cent last year and 43.4 per cent
this year.
Mr David Blunkett, shadow education secretary, claimed to have 'leap-frogged
the Tories' with a pledge for a future Labour government to publish even
more information. He promised to 'highlight schools which are showing real
improvements year-on-year in exam results', and to develop tables which
showed 'how much added value a school has achieved for a pupil' between
their entry to secondary school and their final exams.
Teachers' unions remained critical. Mr Doug McAvoy, general secretary of the
National Union of Teachers, said: 'They show what anyone with any sense
would expect - exam results reflect social background.'
A number of local authorities criticised the government's calculations of
truancy levels in primary and secondary schools. Manchester, which tops the
secondary school truancy table, claimed the figures excluded about 11,000
pupils from a total of 60,000. In one Manchester school, the figures
suggested that 30 per cent of pupils were playing truant at any one time.
Kensington and Chelsea, placed second behind Manchester in the truancy
table, said the government's calculation of the level of truancy among its
secondary school pupils was exaggerated by nearly a quarter. The authority
said that one of its schools had made an error when filing its return and
that Department for Education officials had refused to alter it. However the
department said local authorities had been given the opportunity to check
their schools' submissions.
League tables, Pages 14-16
Tabs on truancy, Page 19
Editorial Comment, Page 23
</TEXT>
