<HEADLINE>
FT  22 NOV 94 / Tory chief warns big pay rises cause 'real offence'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Conservative party campaign strategy document says 'excessive executive
pay packages, especially in the privatised utilities, cause real offence'
and calls for increased taxation of executive share option schemes.
The disclosure of further details from the draft paper, excerpts from which
were published yesterday by the Financial Times, is likely to embarrass the
government in the wake of the Pounds 205,000 pay rise given to Mr Cedric
Brown, the chief executive of British Gas.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, said yesterday: 'What
British Gas have done is broadly to say 'we are a world class company'.' But
the campaign paper, by Mr John Maples, the party's deputy chairman, said
such pay rises cause 'real offence' - a view understood to be shared by Mr
John Major, the prime minister.
The strategy for improving the party's image before the next election,
prepared for Mr Major and Conservative central office, is based on
interviews with 80 disenchanted Conservative voters on average income. They
are described as seeing the government as 'ineffectual and unable to deliver
on its promises'.
The paper says: 'Could we in the future tax share options as income not
capital gains and introduce some level of options above which tax would be
changed as they rise in value not just when they are exercised.'
This proposal to curb the substantial profits from option schemes available
to directors of public companies is broadly similar to the Labour party's
policy.
A furore was also caused yesterday by the suggestion in the paper that the
government consider 'postponing some of April's proposed tax rises if fiscal
conditions permit'.
The paper continued: 'Delaying implementing the second instalment of VAT on
fuel would be dramatic.' Many Tory backbenchers backed this proposal. Mr
Jeremy Hanley, party chairman, told BBC Radio's PM programme yesterday that
there were people 'who believe that the second tranche of VAT on fuel is
uncomfortable for them'.
The paper also proposes 'changes to the pace of NHS reform, eg not pursuing
further performance pay for doctors'.
Mrs Ann Taylor, the shadow leader of the Commons, last night wrote to Mr
Major urging him to 'categorically repudiate the tactics proposed by Mr
Maples'. The paper also says that 'we really must use the Parliamentary
timetable, debates, ministerial statement etc' to control the political
agenda.
Mrs Taylor said this and other suggestions, such as that Tory backbench
'yobbos' metaphorically beat up Labour leader, Mr Tony Blair, were 'an abuse
of both parliamentary procedure and the principle that government should
govern in the national interest'. Miss Betty Boothroyd, the Speaker,
indicated she would 'deprecate' any behaviour which could be seen as
parliamentary yobbery.
